Hello,

Using version 4.4.0, [@CJxD ](https://github.com/exceljs/exceljs/issues/1567#issuecomment-2374347682) fix did not work for me, I found this following solution.
I simply delete ALL the old keys in sheet._merges before, then I call sheet.mergeCells on the new cell coordinates.


```javascript
function update_merged_cells(sheet, start_row, added_rows) {
    // Update Merged cells after start_row when inserting new rows (do not fix merged cells when inserting columns)
    if (added_rows == 0) { return }
    let cell_to_remerge = []
    for (const key of Object.keys(sheet._merges)) {
        let cell = sheet._merges[key];
        if (cell.top >= start_row) {
            cell_to_remerge.push({'top': cell.top + added_rows, 'bottom': cell.bottom + added_rows, 'left': cell.left, 'right': cell.right});
            delete sheet._merges[key];
        }
    }

    for (const range of cell_to_remerge) {
        sheet.mergeCells(range.top, range.left, range.bottom, range.right);
    }
}
```

How I use it :
This will shift the merging of the cells that was defined initially starting row 20, if you inserted `offset` rows before row 20.
```javascript
update_merged_cells(sheet, 20, offset) 
```

Or anytime you insert a row
```javascript
const new_row = sheet.insertRow(rowIndex, row_ref._cells.map(x => zoneDescription));
update_merged_cells(sheet, rowIndex, 1)
```
